    <title>Combined summary - Reorgs on SigNet - Looking for feedback on approach and parameters</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T01:35:30.126539+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-September/019463.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin development community has been discussing the use of Signet as a way to simplify testing, particularly with regards to re-org behavior. One suggestion made during the discussion was to allow SigNet users to opt-out of reorgs if they don't want to be affected by them, while another proposal involved using a different reorg signing key instead. The frequency and depth of reorganizations on the Signet network are also being debated, with some suggesting frequent reorgs every 8 hours would be convenient for testing purposes, while others feel that too frequent reorgs could cause problems for other SigNet users.There is also debate about the purpose of Signet and its target users, with some arguing that it is best suited for integration testing across many services or for users seeing if a service works as expected in a nearly-live environment. Matt Corallo suggests that matching mainnet's behavior may not be an effective way of testing applications. Instead, he suggests that the goal should be to make testing easier and less time-consuming. Proposals have been made to implement planned chain reorganizations on SigNet, considering two scenarios for implementation within the current SigNet miner script. These include a race scenario where two chains compete for D blocks and a chain rollback scenario where the top D blocks get replaced by a chain that outgrows the earlier branch. Feedback is being sought on how often reorgs should happen on default SigNet, with some suggesting 3 reorgs per day, each 48 blocks apart. There are concerns about nodes rejecting higher work chains or double-spending transactions across two chains, which could potentially partition the peer-to-peer network. A quick draft of code for "-signetacceptreorg=0" has been made available to address this issue. There is also a concern about the complexity of implementing a version bit flag for blocks that won't end up in the most work chain.The aim of Signet is to allow software to use it without modification, which requires keeping the header format the same to let SPV clients function without significant modification. Private signets have an advantage over regtest as there is no risk of a random participant causing major reorgs, and it can reasonably be used over the internet without having to worry too much about securing things. Overall, the discussion aims to find the best way to simulate mainnet behavior while allowing for easy testing of applications. The Bitcoin development community is seeking feedback on the approach and parameters for implementing planned chain reorganizations, and the ideal interval and depth for reorgs in the SigNet testing environment.</summary>
